        "body": "Stanza 2 launches from the lowest register of the earth and ascends. The movement is structural and polemical. By beginning with *tehom* — the deep, the primordial abyss — the psalmist is doing to ancient Near Eastern mythology what stanza 1 did to astral religion: de-mythologizing and re-consecrating. *Tehom* shares a linguistic root with the Babylonian chaos-goddess *Tiamat*, slain in the *Enuma Elish* to make the world. In Genesis 1:2 *tehom* is already demoted — the Spirit of God simply moves over it, and it offers no resistance. Here in Psalm 148 it is given a voice, but that voice is *praise*. The threatening depth is not suppressed or destroyed; it is converted into a worshipper.\n\nSea monsters (*tan*) alongside the deeps (148:7) complete the de-mythologizing move. Ancient cosmologies populated the abyss with divine or semi-divine creatures; Israel's psalms repeatedly locate those creatures under God's sovereign command (cf. Psalm 74:13-14; Job 41). Verse 8 moves upward into the atmosphere: fire (lightning), hail, snow, clouds, stormy wind. The crucial phrase is 'fulfilling His word' (*osehem devaro*) — the storm is not random but obedient. This is the psalm's most direct statement about natural phenomena: weather events are the execution of divine commands, not autonomous forces. Spurgeon, on this verse, notes that 'the most terrible and irregular of natural forces is in the service of the most regular of lords.'\n\nVerses 9-10 move through the fixed features of the landscape (mountains, hills) and the living world (fruit trees, cedars, wild animals, cattle, creeping things, flying birds) in what amounts to a liturgical recapitulation of Genesis 1:11-25. The sequence is not accidental — the psalm is deliberately mirroring the creation order, as if summoning creation back to its original vocation. In Genesis 1 each category was called good (*tov*) — here each category is called to make its goodness vocal in praise.\n\nThe stanza reaches its apex in humanity (148:11-12). The social range is comprehensive: kings and peoples (horizontal range — the entire political world), princes and judges (the exercise of power), young men and virgins, old men and children (the vertical range of age). No category is elevated above the call; none is below it. The king must praise alongside the child. The judge must praise alongside the youth. The universality of the summons is the psalm's democratic moment — but its democracy is grounded not in human equality but in shared creaturely status before the one Creator.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Tehom* (deep, v.7) — the primordial abyss; cognate with Akkadian *Tiamat*. *Tan* (sea monsters, v.7) — the same creatures God made and 'saw that they were good' (Genesis 1:21). *Ruach* (wind, v.8) — the same word as 'Spirit' in Genesis 1:2; the connection is lexical, not exegetical, but suggestive. *Osehem devaro* — 'doing/fulfilling His word' — wind as obedient messenger."
