        "body": "Verse 13 is the psalm's theological summit and its most direct claim. The formula 'Let them praise the name of the LORD' mirrors 148:5a and formally closes the earthly stanza. But the grounding clause that follows goes further than 148:5-6. There the reason was creation (*He commanded and they were created*). Here it is transcendence: 'His name alone is exalted; His glory is above earth and heaven.'\n\nThe word *bad* — 'alone' — carries sharp exclusivity. It does not say God is most exalted; it says He is *alone* exalted, in a category by Himself. This is the Hebrew grammar of strict monotheism: not henotheism (one god preferred above others) but the unique dignity of the one God who has no peer. Isaiah 42:8 uses the same logic: 'I am the LORD, that is My name; I will not give My glory to another.' The universal praise-call of 148:1-12 is validated by this claim — if there were other legitimate objects of worship the summons would be arbitrary. Because there is only one Name worthy of exaltation, the command 'everyone praise Him' is not imperialism but precision.\n\nThe second clause — 'His glory is above earth and heaven' — completes the spatial frame the psalm opened in 148:1 (*from the heavens*) and 148:7 (*from the earth*). Earth and heaven together constitute the totality of creation; God's glory transcends that totality. This is not spatial language describing where God lives but ontological language describing the incommensurability between Creator and creation. Calvin comments here: 'The praise of angels and the praise of all the earth cannot begin to match the dignity of the object — it is fitting, not merely commanded.'\n\nThe pastoral implication for Israel — and for the church — is directly practical. If God's glory exceeds earth and heaven, then no circumstance of life, no political reality, no physical suffering lies outside the frame of His sovereign dignity. Praise in Psalm 148 is never escapism; it is the accurate response to the most sober fact about reality: that the one who made everything is irreducibly, exclusively, permanently exalted above it.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Shem* (name, v.13) — not merely a label but the full character of God as disclosed in covenant. *Bad* (alone) — absolute exclusivity; appears similarly in Deuteronomy 32:12 ('the LORD alone led him'). *Hod* (glory/splendor) — the majestic bearing of a great king; distinct from *kabod* (weightiness) but often parallel."
